Vulnerability Name: Horizontal Privilege Escalation - User Id control in request
Severity: High
OWASP Category: A01:2025 – Broken Access Control
Objective: To gain full access into another user's account agfter logging in into one account.
Impact: A user can get full access to another user’s account and perform activites they are unauthorised to do.
Step 1 – User Authentication
        Logged into the application using the provided user credentials.
Step 2 - Request Interception
        Entered a test email in the Update Email section and intercepted the request using Burp           Suite.
Step 3 – Parameter Analysis
        It was observed that User id information was present with the request. Original Value:            id = wiener
Step 4 - Parameter Manipulation
        The user id was modified from id = wiener to id = carlos.
Step 5 - Forwarding the request
        This modified request was then forwarded and the application was refreshed.
Step 6 - Result
        The access to carlos' account was successfully obtained. 

Remediation: 
Enforce server-side authorization checks for every request.
Never rely on user-controlled identifiers for access decisions.
Validate ownership of resources before processing requests.
Implement proper access control policies using authenticated session data.
Apply the principle of least privilege.

Key Learning: 
Access control decisions should always be validated on the server side. User identifiers received from client requests should never determine authorization privileges.




